<TITLE> India, Pakistan agree to punish terrorists swiftly </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI 4 July 2007 (bdnews24.com/AP) Longtime rivals Pakistan and India agreed to crack down on terrorists and drug traffickers during a regular security dialogue, officials said. "Both sides strongly condemned all acts of terrorism and underlined the imperative need for effective and sustained measures against terrorist activities," said a joint statement issued late Tuesday by the two country's home ministers. The three-day meeting was scheduled to run through Wednesday, but Interior Secretary Syed Kamal Shah had to return to Pakistan a day early to deal with a standoff between government forces and armed militants in the capital, an official said. The official was speaking on the condition of anonymity as he was not authorized to make public comments. The two countries also agreed to enhance information sharing and cooperation to stem the tide of cross-border trafficking of drugs and people, the statement said. It did not give any details. The security dialogue is part of a wider peace process between the two sides who have fought three wars since their partition from Britain in 1947, two of them over the disputed Himalayan region of Kashmir. The two sides started discussing the Kashmir issue in 2004 after Islamabad pledged not to allow its territory to be used for terrorist activities. India accuses Pakistan of training and arming Islamic militants who have been fighting for Kashmir's independence from India or its merger with Pakistan since 1989. Pakistan denies the charge. The ministers also agreed to release by mid-August prisoners who have been granted consular access, whose national status has been verified and who have completed their prison sentences, the statement said. India and Pakistan have released hundreds of each other's prisoners as part of peace initiatives. Pakistan says there are 513 Pakistanis in Indian jails. Nearly 500 Indian fishermen are in Pakistan's custody, the Press Trust of India news agency sa
